records.projectDescription:
Our long-term goal is to develop, evaluate, and implement a healthcare provider training program in Zambia to reduce intersecting stigma in clinical settings, improve the quality of integrated sexual health care, and increase gay and bisexual men and other men who have sex with men (GBMSM)’s linkage to the treatment cascade. The specific aims of this mixed-method study include:
Aim #1: Identify drivers/facilitators and manifestations of intersecting stigma against GBMSM in clinical settings in Zambia from the perspectives of culture, religion, law, social policy, and health practices through policy reviews and in-depth qualitative interviews with 20 GBMSM, 20 healthcare providers, and 10 key stakeholders (community leaders and policy-makers);
Aim #2: Explore the effects of intersecting stigma and potential mechanisms of these effects in clinical settings on GBMSM’s (dis)engagement in the HIV treatment cascade through quantitative surveys among 200 MSM and 200 healthcare providers, especially, examining the relative contribution and interactive effects of various components of intersecting stigma on GBMSM’s (dis)engagement in the HIV treatment cascade;
Aim #3: Identify the needs and effective strategies for stigma reduction interventions in clinical settings in Zambia (and potentially other LMICs) via data triangulation in order to develop a healthcare provider intervention to reduce intersecting stigma against GBMSM in clinical settings and to improve GBMSM’s linkage to the HIV treatment cascade in Zambia.
